Here's an example of how you can create a simple search bar using PHP and MySQL. This example assumes that you have a database set up with a table called `books` that has columns for `id`, `title`, and `author`.

**index.php**
```php
<?php
// Connect to the database
$conn = new mysqli('localhost', 'username', 'password', 'database_name');

// Check connection
if ($conn->connect_error) {
    die("Connection failed: " . $conn->connect_error);
}

// Get search query from user input
$search_query = $_GET['search'];

// SQL query to select books that match the search query
$sql = "SELECT * FROM books WHERE title LIKE '%$search_query%' OR author LIKE '%$search_query%'";
$result = $conn->query($sql);

// Display search results
echo '<h2>Search Results:</h2>';
if ($result->num_rows > 0) {
    while ($row = $result->fetch_assoc()) {
        echo 'Title: ' . $row['title'] . ', Author: ' . $row['author'] . '<br>';
    }
} else {
    echo "No results found.";
}

// Close the database connection
$conn->close();
?>
```

**search_bar.html**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        input[type="text"] {
            width: 50%;
            height: 30px;
            font-size: 16px;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
        }

        button[type="submit"] {
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px 20px;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h2>Search Books:</h2>
    <form action="<?php echo $_SERVER['PHP_SELF']; ?>" method="get">
        <input type="text" name="search" placeholder="Enter search query...">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>

    <!-- Display search results -->
    <?php include 'index.php'; ?>
</body>
</html>
```

This code creates a simple search bar that uses GET requests to retrieve the user's input and execute an SQL query to select books from the database. The search query is then displayed on the page.

Please note that this example uses `LIKE` operator which can lead to performance issues with large databases. A better approach would be using full-text indexing and searching, like [MySQL Full-Text Search](https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/fulltext-search.html).

Also, make sure to replace `'localhost'`, `'username'`, `'password'` and `'database_name'` with your actual database credentials.

**Security Note:**

This example uses GET requests for simplicity, but using GET requests can lead to security issues like SQL injection attacks if not properly sanitized. Consider using POST requests or prepared statements instead.

You should also use a prepared statement (like PDO) to avoid SQL injections:
```php
$stmt = $conn->prepare("SELECT * FROM books WHERE title LIKE :search OR author LIKE :search");
$stmt->bindParam(':search', $search_query);
$stmt->execute();
```
**Example Use Case:**

1. Create a new MySQL database and table `books` with columns for `id`, `title`, and `author`.
2. Insert some sample data into the `books` table.
3. Open `index.php` in your web browser to view the search bar.
4. Enter a search query (e.g., "Harry Potter") in the search box and click the Search button.
5. The results will be displayed below the search bar, showing books that match the search query.

Remember to replace `'localhost'`, `'username'`, `'password'` and `'database_name'` with your actual database credentials.

